A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
Now, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of U.S. governments enacted new laws from 2009 onwards making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon grew in scale after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 States were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the periods of voting in advance, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the election and remove citizens with a judicial file from their right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The Supreme Court of the United States in 2008 confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity card.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required ID card.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affecting young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over the age of 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID card.
More than that.
Students, who are considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
Two out of three Hispanic voters are in favour of the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers sponsored laws that abolished voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states to shorten the voting period in advance.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state voters.
It was the same with the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of voters, represented only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have vehemently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undeniably make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that the states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: pass the test or not?
In fact, the APS test would sometimes have erroneous results, with false negative or false positive results, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
What makes even more hesitant men already reluctant to pass screening tests.
Pass the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two specialists.
