Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had a screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, with a follow-up after 12 years, that you are between 30 and 40% more likely to have metastases if you are not detected.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40 if you have a direct parent who has already had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at greater risk.
The key is to make the right decision once cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
It is really necessary to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer, by offering him the possible options, not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and instead opting, in those cases, for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men in whom cancer is detected will not be treated, because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest that they do active surveillance, and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
