The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole emotion, last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "lesser" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet entirely certain that it is Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it looks a lot like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely sure.
Let's assume it's Higgs anyway, since the chances of being wrong seem thin, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this low world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot end up in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Now, even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting grosso modo in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In a corner, there are good citizens named Fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would somehow appear.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not all as exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messaging" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, a bit like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "carrying force".
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for that boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond with only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what "can" all this research bring, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between observations and predictions of MS.
In fact, there are many who are keen to find one, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physical" and clog some holes in the Model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (hopefully!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter in the Universe (re-hopefully!).
But no such differences have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Mr and Mrs All-the-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be no such repercussions.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work was going to unleash.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - told us fire, at first the laser was rather seen as a "lab gadget".
I can imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work on optics.
This sensor, although it was not its original intention at all, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and won it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that LHC activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
