With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec has recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate should resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this essential area.
The Duty tried to take a closer look at it.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in La Montérégie.
The cancer of the prostate that gnawed him had left him a two-year respite.
"They gave me five years to live, I've been seven years," he said, half-fig half-grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an enormous weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Stuck in front of an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even happens to smile, talks to strangers who deal with him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man urinates standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Regressing to the stage of the child, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
For, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the "team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and suffocated.”
But the disease made me discover my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life," she says, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
However, in the next few days, she expects a last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and nutrition assistance.
These are palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know we all end up dying someday.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the house.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Upon death, we will agree to provide oral care to brandy or Pepsi, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died overnight.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, well tucked into his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old young man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to relieve suffering when a patient reaches the end of his or her life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Society for Palliative Care at Home in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that causes several palliative care specialists to fear the adoption of a law that governs euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care summits including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient spend 14 days in the emergency room, in great pain, without doing what is necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients are only asking to die because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are stalking their patients to the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helene Richard’s life expectancy was already low when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
Still, she told me I was done!
No All-Powerful Care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the caregivers for not having accessed their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Society of Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which involves sleeping the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
