A Forceps Constitution in Egypt
This is a new poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily gives it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state gave this House two more months to finish its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "betray his word" and "troll the law".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time that compels the Brothers to renounce their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest is raging across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
This hasty vote is based on an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "You either vote for my text or I retain full powers", which is supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had knocked on the door, believing that they had not been able to assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimous that the articles were voted on.
Commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the constituent's pendulum was poorly regulated.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
In the end, article 2 remains the same as the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of sharia are the primary source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a pledge of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals respond, who see it as a blow to communication.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
In particular, they refer to Article 220, which confers on Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question could in the future be the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extended powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the former regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defense Council.
Civilian trials in military courts will not be banned, as was demanded by human rights associations.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider liberticid.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, no article echoes the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the Center of the World and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argumenty i Fakty took five great reasons to go to Israel.
Go and adore the holy places
Make yourself unavoidable: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these “baptismal grounds” will be touched by Divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is in this very place that Jesus appeared to His disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the Antonia fortress (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the burial.
This is where the Christian center of the world stands, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations which constitutes the remainder of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different confessions leave small words accompanied by prayers that are then answered.
Travel in Height
Visit the ruins of the fortress Massada, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are 45 km long.
The old beliefs want pagan gods to once inhabit the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
The country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth checking out.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (the parliament).
It is home to the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly displays the impressionist and expressionist paintings of Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of mouldings of visitors and observers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children’s memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter it in total darkness.
The stars are shining.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned here.
Health and well-being
The three major seaside resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surreal beauty.
We come to perform treatment based on salt water, lemon, healing sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shore of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to walk through the narrow alleys that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take photo sessions from all of Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Ponce Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera shows.
Note to tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (now 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, these are mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and able to connect the low and high parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition is to celebrate the Sabbath on the Sabbath.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop operating.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve kosher food only, excluding pork, seafood, unscathed fish and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, molten chichi peas balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of well-fed cats that walk around looking tall.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be pampered.
Renting a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels per day.
Entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Which language has, to Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While lawmakers and human rights activists are controversy over what the mandatory language test law will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already made their appearance in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time they are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has entered into force and stipulates that every migrant worker must pass a Russian exam.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, private services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Immigration Service promises, tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your Russian language skills in order to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or diplomas of teaching before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Profit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the auspices of the Russian Language Institute Pushkin, the University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions of Russia.
Immigrants will be able to pass the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the territory.
This initiative to introduce reviews has been supported by Members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders had already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what is it going to do?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First, according to the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says Victor Sebelev, director of the office of the Russian Federal Service for Migration in Tajikistan.
Protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without an understanding of the language, Sebelev confirms, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded cottage where he and dozens of his fellows will torment themselves for months without food and without paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are deceived, they take their passports, and they do not get the salary they expect," said Tolib Charipov, the head of the Migration Services Directorate for the work of Tajikistan's migration service.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to come to make money in Russia trust that they not only do not know the language of the country where they want to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but rather their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a passable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have anything to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people start earning money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
Examinations will only be for migrants who have legal status.
Without statutes, there will be no official examination or work afterwards.
Yet, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to get official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we have no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Oumed Khuchkadamov, a Tajik national, told reporters.
“Hurry up, don’t lose weight and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration papers of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false certificates of language examinations have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
Fake paper comes out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of exams had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: this will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Representatives of power and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paperbags”.
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first time exam to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered a job in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapons carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it was the shootings carried out during the weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the carrying of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a permit to carry a weapon by increasing it from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma’s committee for security and anti-corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is satisfied to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were registered during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that tightening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from supplying themselves to the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from the factory to the officer
The black market of weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking gun controls
The first is the "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by the Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals to law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stockpiles and stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal guns go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
"Certified versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to conceal the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition on the international market and run out of weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow,” one expert says.
