Childbirth in Space
The Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a deadly asteroid.
Caravans of space shuttles with landers on board set out in search of a rescue planet.
To save humanity, a big question arises: how can we continue to make our species live in weightlessness or on a rescue planet?
I don't think there's much to choose from.
There are actually two real planets that can be conquered, even if only by hypothesis.
"It's about Venus and Mars," says Vladimir Sourdine, a researcher at the P.K. Chternberg State Astronomical Institute (GAICh).
If on Mars the conditions are more suitable for life, the temperature on the surface of Venus is 500.
We can only live there at very high altitudes or on the orbit of Venus... in space.
We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on the flora.
Half a century ago, we were experimenting with plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from earthly varieties.
Then, we put on orbit insects, small reproductive drosophilic flies.
In 1979, cauliflower eggs were sent into space to see how an unweighted embryo was developing.
At the exit we get a completely normal chick.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick needs to find support, it needs to get on its legs and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
In finding no support, the chicks were stirring in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophied.
The chicks did not respond to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
“We peeled their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological miniature ark with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the Bion biosatellite will only ship same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
"It was still about biosatellites and then it's the only experiment. We have to do this kind of research ", says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats gave birth to their offspring.
However, it is not yet possible to perform reproductions directly in space.
It's not a small business.
By losing their usual environment, animals are no longer able to realize their sexual instincts.
Unlike animals, man is capable of it, in principle.
Homo sapiens possesses abstract thought, it is able to create a suitable emotional background.
This type of experience is not carried out for ethical reasons.
But women have been going into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was taken by Terechkova.
And the female organism is what humanity has most precious.
Our mussel flew and no one on Earth could tell if it would hold up after a flight into space.
If she could have given birth to a child after the flight.
“No one was answering that question,” said Vakhtang Vatchnadze, a retired space and rocket scientist.
In June 1964, just a year after her flight into space, the first woman cosmonaut Valentina Terechkova gave birth to a little girl.
The child's father, Andrian Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman cosmonaut Svetlana Savitskaya, after having been in orbit twice and even worked in an extra-vehicular environment, gave birth to a son.
However, the risk persists.
We have few, even very few cosmonauts who have had nothing and who give birth to a healthy offspring after long flights.
"And if they are longer, it presents a danger even during orbital flights," concludes the pilot and cosmonaut, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of Russia, Valeriy Poliakov.
