Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of ESA projects.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles worked on spaceflights; they did not always meet understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas drawn from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the auditors cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld received in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
This doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a drainage plant was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the drain.
The only information known about this drasin is that of the press at the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the preserved documents that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year was published the book "Raketa - torpedo azymna i rakietobomba lutnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were conducted by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronauticze).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problème, which contains four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowiczze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronomy.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and as early as autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakeita Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket, developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM-type rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B that volume was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision has sparked a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to examine this issue from a broader point of view.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
In concrete terms, this means that the various economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of freedom of trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital allied to unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wages) generate tension on prices.
The following meaning should be interpreted as meaning that a producer endeavours, by importing goods sold at a low price, to resist economic competition by "increasing" the price of the competitor, with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thereby increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, or buying at low prices, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the state necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect bad will of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damages caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so publicly known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to enter into a mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the dictate of private capital prices, especially in the field of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the case of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of workers' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and the deepening of the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot support their needs with their own work.
The number of these people is already counted by millions.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is forced to pay a surcharge in order for them to reach the minimum standard of living.
For example, such a scandal has been updated in the case of employees working as assistants to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with wages of misery, in the margins of society.
The question is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian, or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media are tired of saying that the state cannot invest capital in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
It is then necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence and even direct today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and, by itself, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby that exists in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, by granting mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that, due to the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of bills to law firms closely related to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The entirety of power does not come from the people, as stated in the constitutions of the Western type, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his work entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state was long in full deliquescence and the functions were assigned by violence.
The bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The under-the-table and corruption were proliferating without limits and the people were going to the elections with votes already sold" ... ... "Honest people did not seek to obtain functions, it resulted once the state was left 8 months without consuls".... ' It really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy "
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
As a result, today as in the past, there has been an unprecedented decadence of elites, without any effort to carry out in-depth reforms.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems in favour of liberal-style democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of human lives, the humanitarian and social crises we are witnessing today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both internationally and internally at European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the investment of state capital in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
