The film Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a mob of protesters made up of Islamist students stormed the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, in fact, it could not abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, further exacerbated later by the fiasco of the attempted release of the hostages by force.
The kidnapped diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused in the United States a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After difficult journeys, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rock-and-roll cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team who came to make footage for the shooting of a science-fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez received collaboration from Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
The Affleck film is an unusual combination of several genres.
This is partly a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a caper movie, the story of a successful hit, a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The ambiances follow: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the epoch of events and the way, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been transcribed in the film, there are no big differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck was able to start his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting has ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film after the dark policeman Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The Town (2010).
It is also the first Affleck film not to take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of a place's atmosphere is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran’s bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director must have been content with a subject that actually offers few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He is doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway are quite hair-drawn).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it’s true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-workers, their characters would have deserved a bigger place and they’re not, by far, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it lets itself be seen with a moderate interest, enjoying the direction and retro style of the 1970s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of yet another story, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he makes the case.
