The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To convince yourself of it, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large nearby company, tells us, "Yes, it's really beautiful, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one goes to one of those sloppy libraries anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper city that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The 80,000-soul municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to return some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to take back the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architects' office MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mindful and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented to the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a richness on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, baffled and shouldering, Maas, the outcast, piled up his books of choice in order of size to make them a pyramid, and ended his argument-based speech with an "common dear!"
Here’s my proposal for the mountain of Spijkenisse’s books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain sprouted from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and semi-detached houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this small dull village, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of a stunning uglyness, whose white facades invite you to think that they shelter a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you step on the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lights unequivocally speak the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and little girls who play ball.
And everywhere books, books, and more books.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," Maas explains.
We completely changed the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been neatly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambris, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers don’t want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager for the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in an agricultural enterprise frisson an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes with a thickness of one millimeter have been used for years as substrates in greenhouses and fields.
It is cheap and saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to the maintenance of the ideal humidity level of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
“It’s amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books lies beneath a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of good weather.
Thick wooden beams mounted crosswise relative to the glass facade serve as a sunshade, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambiance is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally found soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the voids in the library that was not yet fully secured (today it counts 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
According to Winy Maas, “There is nothing worse than a half-empty library.”
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between each citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request to obtain observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but not to be too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany also opted for abstention in the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
In the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still striving to find this role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term “normal” foreign policy mean to the Germans?
It demonstrates a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national cases.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, as this is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is at least a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Is Germany damaging its relations with the United States by choosing to abstain in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think the Europeans and the Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
The United States, on the other hand, has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
