"Mark Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but that has nothing to do with the original company.
The trademark thus enjoys protection such that the company that bears the name of it cannot file a complaint.
And even if she could, it's not sure she'd win a case.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in property infringement in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives at my desk.
Imitators only need a few extra letters to register their trademarks.
Thus, instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the sportswear manufacturer.
Pattloch opens a notebook in which are the recordings made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the Zegna DF Puma trademark, a name that the firm artificially created by owning part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually only counterfeit goods.
Pattloch’s cases, however, are different: his clients charge him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially gives Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese are talking about "Bang Mingpai", a related brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is by this term that women are referred to as those who marry rich men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame.
“It’s bad for business, we have to fight this trend,” Pattloch said.
"The brand is sweetened, the uniqueness disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs are in the millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>15 billion, the world’s third-largest market for luxury products and the fastest growing.
However, it is not easy to delete dubious registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch reports the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long period, the criticized denomination had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay the plagiarist money, as he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
This is why the Chinese can use an emblem that resembles the Mercedes star.
Geely, the Volvo buyer, used a blue-and-white logo that resembled that of BMW, and the conflict was resolved and Geely had to modify it.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost against the plagiarists of Hong Kong and Singapore who had redirected the famous crocodile’s gaze in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits, however, that it experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the office would have gone last year from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a normality found".
Thus, the number of untreated opposition proceedings would have fallen by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 cases of this type would have been closed, representing a 75% increase from the previous year.
Nonetheless, 81,500 proceedings remain pending at the office.
Acting is expensive
As often in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
According to the office, this is a record and it means that China is at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world for the tenth time in a row.
This would also apply to the total number of trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the office reportedly accounted for 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record reported an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been battling a Chinese plagiarism.
Indeed, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components to be suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“It’s our fault, because family names can’t be protected in Germany,” said Hanno Wentzler, president of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office therefore rejected the Munichers' objection.
Freudenberg certainly won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing party continues to fight to this day.
Vigilance is at stake
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
However, he adds, "the procedure is long, tempting and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to estimate internal costs, and the Archives Service has even had to review the records of the last hundred years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg even offered in vain to the opposing party a "six-digit large sum in euros" to settle the dispute.
“That’s what we see what this means for us,” Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to overflow to Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file the name Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long since abandoned this sector, but it was still able to prevent the filing.
Wentzler adds, "vigilance is a must."
Pattloch and him advise German companies to be very cautious in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, according to them, to rely on international trademark law, rather foreigners should "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle during the last act of its legal drama, the company should pay licensing fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as explained by Wentzler.
Otherwise, we would lose our place in the market segment in question.
