Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorrhagia (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and gall belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and blennorrhagia often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men causes at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, infections related to chlamydia, trichomonases, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhagia and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, however, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, Chlamydia-related infections are significantly higher than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Moreover, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to declare all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been decreasing.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white loss, lower abdominal pain, as well as the appearance of buds and warts.
However, they regularly cause no pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close body contacts.
Therefore, experts recommend that any person who frequently changes sexual partners take regular exams.
Most quickly detected STIs can be cured and delayed sequelae can be avoided.
