After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained by the military.
The state must also, as the draft reads, protect “the true nature of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values”.
From a legal point of view, the formulation is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematography and literature.
