Norway rakfisk: is it the most odorous fish in the world?
The five million people who inhabit Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards, not only in Europe but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country’s success be linked to the locals’ appetite for an extremely smelly fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty footwear.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway’s most popular dishes.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this odor, ubiquitous, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of salt sprinkled trout and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness settles and it is cold, Norwegians gather in masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
“You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit,” says Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as ‘Rakfisk General’, who is responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and pour a large amount of drink.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk," Havard adds.
Drinking kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it’s not bad – it reminds you of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels and then salted in the fall.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish came out and - undoubtedly with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Nowadays, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, crossed the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered something important, a vital, though odorous, element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 <0xE2><0x82><0xAC> each.
Norway does not often speak about it in international news, which is not to his displeasure.
