Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a tough start.
As incumbent President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, the BBC's Will Grant is interested in the challenges ahead and the expectations of the people, which are many.
The road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where traffic jams are legion in normal time, a security dam has been in place since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
Nonetheless, the goal was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, the new president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the new president at the head of the nation.
A complicated task awaits you.
Mexico’s economy is doing well, with results due to outgoing President Felipe Calderon, but the country is in a drug war that has already cost the lives of about 60,000 people in six years.
“My government has made a commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office a little earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before joining the US president, Mr. Pena Nieto was governor of the state of Mexico.
A very populous and sprawling state that encloses the capital. On its preferred land, opinions about this new leader are divided.
A direct man
In the bucolic community of Valle del Bravo, for example, it is inscribed in the memory of all.
