However, this is exactly what the family has been denied.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old commer, a troublemaker, a weeping woman.
They want us to accept what they say and keep quiet.
“But it is not normal that there are so many irregularities and omissions,” she said.
When President Pena Nieto receives his scarf on Saturday, it will be accompanied by heavy responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by crime in Mexico over the past six years, and the new president has promised to make it his priority during his term.
“I hope he will be as good as when he was governor,” said Olvera, a member of Congress in Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecutors said.
Prosecutors are trying to counter allegations of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning allegedly suffered during detention.
The trial is about Manning’s detention at a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants to classify the case on the grounds that Manning's seizure took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the largest leak of confidential information in the entire history of the U.S. military -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During a counter-interrogation with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Major Ashden Fein claimed that recordings of weekly visits made to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The counter-interrogation -- during a hearing, the defense filed a petition demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the seizure took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified his desire to commit suicide during his tenure.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention at the military prison of Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment his guards had reserved for him was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received within the prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain problems and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems mentioned.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and yet that didn't mean I didn't raise any problems," Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to evoke the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The military said it had assigned it this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for its protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know I was doing well, and I wanted this status to be removed ... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps military prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had contemplated suicide while in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very annoying.
“My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent the clearest part of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items he had at his disposal were a mattress, a blanket, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also clarified that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards could not see his face when he turned at night, they would wake him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning, during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he should let go of his blanket that might have hidden his nudity, but he admitted that no one had ordered him to let go.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his panties or tongs to injure himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, tongs, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account the experiences he experienced during his detention and that he will greatly reduce his sentence if he is found guilty in a martial court, a trial expected to take place early next year.
The defense said Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious crimes and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors arguing that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was detained in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of property or public documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of information related to the national defense.
If all the prosecutions are detained, he is sentenced to life imprisonment.
