Moreover, many Mexican-Americans I know do not feel like they are part of one country or the other.
We love the music of the Mexican band, Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
We have the best of both worlds, but we are not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we are considered Americans.
And in the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
And now, to complicate the relationship a little more, as I learned during my stay, some Mexican leaders and part of the intelligentsia want to get closer to the Diaspora.
They want the Mexican-Americans to work as wealth ambassadors for Mexico, representing its interests in the United States.
We will have to explain to our American compatriots that Mexico is a superb country that we absolutely need to visit and put pressure on political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course.
That's not going to happen.
There's too much bitterness.
And, considering the ubiquitous wage inequality, corruption and drug-related violence, many of us are not convinced that this is a fantastic country.
You're gonna have to deal with it alone, amigos.
That's normal.
