Old quarrels, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such hope is in vain.
While the same futile arguments persist as to who started it, dozens of buildings have been dusted; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets fired from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, the city's capital, and the city's metropolis.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is in full swing.
The Arab Spring has shattered everything, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
Perhaps their struggle will intensify a little more.
Yet there is every reason to think that it could help them get out of this deadly impasse.
A war that makes no losers or winners
At first glance, it seems difficult to be optimistic.
While the November 21 ceasefire continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened supporters of the force on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has led Gaza since 2007, will be proud to have forced the Israelis to give up, even though Gaza has suffered a crackdown.
Having killed some of its leaders and pushed back the 1.7 million Gazans in one of the most miserable and overcrowded corners of the planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently in the hands of their Fatah rivals, the other more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, the leaders of Hamas might say that time is their ally.
The influence of Islamists in the Arab world is growing stronger, and Hamas has made rich and powerful friends.
Turkey, a growing regional power, once Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken action for Hamas, as has Qatar, one of the Gulf’s richest and most dynamic states.
Hamas members rejoice and say that the Islamist rising curves around Israel, from Lebanon, in the north, where the Hezbollah militia is exercising its domination, through Syria, where rebels of Islamist tendency can overthrow Bashar El Assad, and to Jordan, where Hamas allies led the way.
And most importantly, on the southern flank of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under the presidency of Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and central of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time to devote to Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is Hamas’s cousin, and its leaders are more likely to turn to public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas can emerge as an important actor that can no longer be excluded even by Israel and America.
Meanwhile, supporters of Israel’s hardline will draw the opposite conclusions.
In military terms, Hamas has been put back in a box.
The Iron Dome missile interception system proved to be effective and many Hamas missiles were destroyed.
The Israelis will be able to sleep on both ears – for a while.
In terms of diplomacy, America renews its unwavering support; and many European countries have accused Hamas of being the cause of the latest wave of violence.
But above all, Israel prospered, especially under Benjamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, who totally ignored the peace process.
Although rocket fire from Gaza has killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been spared by suicide bombings, notably through the barrier of separation that encroaches on the West Bank, the main chunk of what could be a Palestinian state, and which protects Jewish settlements from international law.
Netanyahu, whose Likud party merged with an even more belligerent party, that of leader Avigdor Lieberman on the approach of the January 22 election, has the nice part.
Why are these Palestinian bastards giving them a state?
If they were to lead the West Bank, wouldn’t they launch rockets, as their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is best to keep them behind this wall and hit them as soon as they come out of the head.
Perhaps the supporters of the hard line will win; but the Arab Spring may change.
Even if the Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel, their priority will be to tackle the problems in their own countries.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the local superpower will not help the new Arab governments to arrange their economies.
Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get a ceasefire, which is good news -- and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis should also think about the future.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination could create a dustbin that is destined to explode one day in Israeli-occupied territories — a bit like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression already weakens democracy in the Jewish state, and demographics exacerbate this problem as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions against Gaza every two or three years to call Hamas will have a diplomatic prize.
Both sides need to be pushed by those on the outside.
The answer remains the one advocated by the reasonable people on either side, and by most of the outside world and by this newspaper: two states, with a transfer of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
One hope, small and short-term, is that the ceasefire will provide an opportunity for outsiders to defend this cause.
