The World's Hardest Job: Kawah Ijen's Human Mules
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilograms of sulfur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh in total nearly 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters to the summit of the volcano that peaks at 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted bearers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, at a turtle’s pace, keeping their balance and measuring their steps to avoid stumbling and falling into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur extracted.
Once up, they make a path between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers up to the scale that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, we can say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry since this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138.000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the fields.
“The income of minors is very high here, where coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not so difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl who ramoui to Bali, where they are Hindus".
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to pay him the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Ruined by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares a mass of unhealthy wood with other wearers, gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning because sulfur does not cease to sprout at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater illuminating himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
About 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to wearers who work on their own and are paid to the weight.
In addition, they also do not touch one of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) of increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old bearer who has been working at Kawah Ijen for 30 years since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can" because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the minors in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which they obviously add their usual breathing problems, deformed by arthritis and stenosis.
By balancing the basket on his back, 53-year-old Unanik can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, his companions and he extracted 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transported to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers from there by a goat trail invaded by weeds.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but perpetuated misery from generation to generation is one of the most difficult jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah Ljen volcano.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this absence of children on the career, stress and cost of access to property.
"The population of Singapore must grow."
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let us fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these words come from an advertisement for mint pills, but despite that, or perhaps thanks to that, the video spread like a powder trail on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a polychine in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way thanks to this ad.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music for people to fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we have been able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt it was a topic we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we said the following: what could be more creative about solving this problem than making it a rap song?
1.2 Children
The Singaporean government is not taking it that lightly.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favor of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
The birth rate of Singapore, according to its national population distribution, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it found itself above 2, considered as the renewal rate, was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, said it was due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has enabled people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and the constitution of a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the population decline has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with xenophobia barely disguised against new immigrants, especially against Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore experienced its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the drop in the birth rate has known effects on a country’s economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has started to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says its “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to promoters, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by discussing with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they will not have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it back to later,” says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
"But for me, it's important to be able to have my money and my time," another 20-year-old told us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the last word.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of privacy that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is the private domain for children under the age of 16?
How to apply this definition in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, ages 10 to 15, frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level and "password and username" when they applied it to social networks.
“I won’t reveal my most personal secrets in a post,” says 10-year-old Jorge when he tries to explain the meaning of the private term on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
"These are very secrets, my mother can know them, but not everyone," he said.
On FB, I post nice pictures or games.
I also talk to my friends.
“I’m not going to share one of my photos or anyone who would be stupid,” he said.
The boy acknowledges that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine Twitter followers.
The majority are from the family.
Her mother is part of it, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they answer me, I just post them,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant parents or my friends, quickly,” he says.
He claims that he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Nor will he trust anyone who would recommend him a stranger.
The case of José, 14 years old, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people on his friends list.
“It doesn’t bother me because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to the boy, no one made any advances or asked for his address or phone number.
“If they were putting pressure on me or demanding it, I would just delete them from my account,” he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences known today as cyberbullying are not foreign to the young boy.
A close friend of mine was racked up on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to José, did not close his account.
"He just took it to a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to set up his account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or angry.
“Even if I know it’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key Issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English and a graduate in Education and Learning, believes that, in order to guide children and adolescents, one must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a way to search for information but, with the advent of these sites, the rule of the game has changed,” she said.
Porras notes that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a master’s degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book “Native and Digital Immigrants,” uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives, they, children and young people are born with technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we ourselves are learning,” she says.
He adds that the theme is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined criterion on what is appropriate to disclose, publish or say at an age where they do not have the necessary maturity to do so."
“We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences.”
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach privacy to children and adolescents is to use questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it is useless,” she says.
Then Porras lists a few examples: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a photo of you like that of a friend you posted?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you’re doing every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
These are the same rules.
“When it comes to the Internet, everyone has to act with respect, morality and other principles, it has to be the same on social media,” she said.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education advisor, says that it is essential that parents carefully read the conditions of use of social networks.
By understanding each of the terms, they will have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an online account.
“For example, the age and what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public.
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven present mandate holders.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit was closed, then claimed that it would be published from one time to the other on the Internet site.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by Peruvian President Ollante Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information on the summit was constantly restricted.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The few reports circulating among journalists were those given by the press attachés of some of the UNASUR governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit's "final statement," but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South American Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although it was urgently requested by the press, it also did not disseminate the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that sets a different border between the two countries.
Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ’s decision to hear the pleas of both parties in the trial that Lima has filed against Santiago and that begins Monday in The Hague.
“We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing today before this international court,” President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties, and international courts,” Piñera said in a statement.
The two presidents’ confirmation that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely erroneous.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been suspended from UNASUR since 2011 following the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR's countries would implement "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship by developing agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphal matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and foresee a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connectivity of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the cross-axis of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not provide further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," he said.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace with good relations with its neighbours is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through a ICJ ruling requested by Bogotá.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will review all of these pathways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask for a discussion with that country," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they planned to attend the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc’s defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of UNASUR, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship," Correa said.
Ecuador's President Rafael Correa said today that the creation of a common citizenship was an objective for which "South America, in this case, should take an example on Europe".
President Correa, who took part in the sixth summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), located in Lima, told state television, TV Peru, that Europeans "had been interspersed during World War II" and other conflicts, "but they were now almost a homeland".
