And if Sweden, as its legislation allows, and as it has already done in other cases, questioned Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or questioned him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took advantage of it to reaffirm himself as a defender of freedom of the press and he clarified that what he did not tolerate were " mediocrity, bad faith and lies that harm freedom of expression."
“The greatest enemies of press freedom are not evil politicians or perverts but bad journalists who are paid for greed, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
From this point of view, he welcomed the fact that it is not this kind of journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador" and, rather than pushing forward his re-election, "it would deepen the revolution to pursue the path and trace the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to keep the veto on Paraguay within UNASUR at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality, "it would destroy the legitimacy of paramocracy".
In addition, the Ecuadorian president considers "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
They must be solved as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the proper resolution of the maritime border dispute between Peru and Chile within the same court and said it was "beneficial for Latin America to bring the international proceedings if both countries agree to accept a judgment as firm as it may be".
Referring to the possibility of his nomination for the upcoming presidential election in Ecuador, for a third consecutive term, he said he saw this opportunity "with a lot of optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 primary, he would retire from public life.
At the personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as those of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we must accept that responsibility," he said.
If I win, it would be my last presidential term and I would then retire from political life.
If we ever lose, I will too.
“It’s my decision,” he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
“This does not mean a relapse of President Chávez’s state of health,” he said.
