Today, AIDS-related deaths are due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to be HIV positive.
“It was as if the sky had fallen on my head,” he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make “less painful,” in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it and his hard work was such that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmata.
Then even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless".
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first cases reported, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV unit of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he took this information in public reference.
The infectiologist and expert on HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists concluded that AIDS was no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and the quality of life depended on the level of affectation of the immune system presented by the patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not consuming 50 years.
Simply put, it means that for someone who would receive an HIV positive diagnosis at age 25, “as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems for up to 75 years,” the scientist interviewed explained.
In order to replace this progress in its context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS has increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients identified on the basis of national data have been diagnosed.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we have never missed medication, the problem is that patients get to very advanced stages because they do not know they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, which is what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality, is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, it is necessary to offer screening tests in a massive way, to all people who ask for it.”
The specialists and members of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as well as the patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already suffering from AIDS.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, it's better if I blow up three times a week," they say, that's not my case.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medications.
To date, his parents only know that he suffers from cancer.
I have a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sexual life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and to the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his privacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march against the Jo Mondiale.
Let them take the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they need to know that you can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, that is very good, but as a result, even today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", posed with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teens don't want to hear, the journalist assures.
He proposes to redirect this ineffective distribution; that condoms should not only be sold to counters, but also be found in public toilet distributors and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had responded when asked if there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
“This is not how sexuality works, it’s best to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,” he said.
Numbers in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state is the 4th country in the number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and the 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of contamination occurs through sexual contact, 6% through blood and 2% through perinatal contact.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for every recorded case there are 4 or 5 people who ignore it.
A judgment ratified in appeal by a U.S. court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt consented through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario creates a damaging precedent for all domestic companies with ramifications in the neighboring country and having solvency problems.
Thus, it seems that the survival procedures of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star-studded flag, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the ruling by Judge Harlin Hale of the North Texas Bankruptcy Court on June 15 left Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of an embargo on their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s main glass manufacturer to sue the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case notes that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
