Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
“Hetin” Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life on the field and, thanks to him, has travelled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a cerebral haemorrhage sentenced him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayer Basket President or Bayer President.
"I have worn several hats in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his 50-year-old fiancée.
“Basketball is my whole life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind him of his out-of-standard itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the team of the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
"These have been my best years, the ones I've enjoyed the most because I've had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
This has been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired during the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great manager, took the lead of the team," Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, "I have a tough player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
This is how Mincy started, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He enjoyed the championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his duties and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian judge hadn’t made us play the last game again,” Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and we put a scratch on the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only made up of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world 90 problem.
A team that may not be the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players suspended by the Imbroglio of the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
Its statistics at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Piculín did.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work Leo Arill does.
What is your biggest success in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN counted up to 17 teams in a season.
What's left for you to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys play only in their area and only face teams from other corners of the island during the national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of compulsory certifications and courses for executives, field staff and referees.
That makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch clips of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide for the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night from complications of cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas".
“Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press attaché, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in the liver and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles in the film are well received by critics in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman experienced his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan “Who Killed J.R.?”, invented to entertain the suspense around an emotional episode in which Hagman’s character is nearly murdered, has generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars played in betting.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had conceived her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to detain his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is the Honest Citizen J.R. Ewing."
Here's the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled this Friday Hagman as a man "immense, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were aired a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is underway, the channel reported.
So far, neither Warner nor TNT have announced how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who met celebrity with such classic works as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 while she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his first steps on the stages of New York theaters in the early 1950s and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life" (in French: Hello Darlin': Les mémoires implacables de J.R.)
"I have not written anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told the press at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist worried patients.
"I advise them, I give them back their trust, I come with them when they have surgery and afterwards," he said in 1996.
I’m trying to offer them some comfort, like “Don’t be afraid, it won’t be easy for a little while, but it’s going to be okay.”
He has also been an anti-tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course dealing with the "end of the world" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the “great countdown” of the Mayan calendar, December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what was awaiting him over the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax loophole that some have dubbed the "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the late Christian theorists would think it would decay.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we tell it, it was a very good time.
And remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he’s not the only professor to give lectures on “the end of the world” this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We’re analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” Restall said.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his high-level student course, consisting of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursing, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic movies.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate that.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end date of the world on December 21.
“Our first project dealt with Maya prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old West Chester-born last year student at Temple.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is a centuries-old anxiety about the apocalypse in Western culture that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in such speculation.
“In other places around the globe, people don’t think about it,” he said.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is giving classes in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that we were giving classes here on "the end of the world."
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, the many supposed dates of the Last Judgment have been discussed, and he claims that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a period of 7 years at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many have told us that they thought they were going to "end of the world" parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
